%U A394100 66,69,69,70,70,75,75,75,75,77,77,78,80,80,81,82,85,85,85,88
%N A394100 Longest sides z for integer-sided triangles (x <= y <= z) with an integer internal angle bisector l splitting the triangle into two integer-sided triangles; include only tuples (x, y, z; l) with gcd(x, y, z, l) = 1; ordered by z, then y, then x.
%C A394100 Isosceles cases occur: y = z or x = y. In an isosceles triangle, the internal bisector at the apex coincides with the altitude (and the median) to the base.
%C A394100 Primitive cases only: gcd(x, y, z, l) = 1. All non-primitive cases arise by scaling a primitive case by integers k > 1.
%C A394100 The middle and shortest sides are listed as A394101 and A394102, respectively. The corresponding l-values are in A393193.
%C A394100 A triangle (x <= y <= z) is included if there exists an internal angle bisector with (i) integer length l = sqrt(y*z*((y + z)^2 - x^2))/(y + z) (or cyclically at y or z), (ii) an integer split of the opposite side x into x*y/(y + z) and x*z/(y + z) (or cyclically), and (iii) gcd(x, y, z, l) = 1.
%C A394100 At most one qualifying bisector: If y + z divides x, then a second such condition would require (x + z) divides y, which together is impossible (would force x >= 2*y and y >= 2*x). Hence at most one internal angle bisector can satisfy the integrality conditions.
%H A394100 Felix Huber, <a href="/A394100/b394100.txt">Table of n, a(n) for n = 1..10000</a>
%H A394100 Felix Huber, <a href="/A394100/a394100.txt">Maple program</a>
%H A394100 Eric Weisstein's World of Mathematics, <a href="https://mathworld.wolfram.com/AngleBisector.html">Angle Bisector</a>
%H A394100 Wikipedia, <a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Angle_bisector_theorem">Angle bisector theorem</a>
%e A394100 6 is a term because in the triangle (x, y, z) = (5, 5, 6) the internal bisector l_z = 4 splits z = 6 into 3 and 3, yielding two congruent triangles (3, 4, 5), and gcd(5, 5, 6, 4) = 1.
%e A394100 18 is a term because in the triangle (x, y, z) = (12, 15, 18) the internal bisector l_y = 10 splits y = 15 into 6 and 9, yielding triangles (6, 10, 12) and (9, 10, 18), and gcd(12, 15, 18, 10) = 1.
%p A394100 # See Huber link.
